11 [(3)] (4) “Fund” means the Maryland Veterans Service Animal Program
12 Fund established under subsection (f) of this section.
13 [(4)] (5) “Nonprofit training entity” means a corporation, a foundation, or
14 any other legal entity that:
15 (i) is qualified under § 501(c)(3) of the Internal Revenue Code;
16 (ii) 1. engages in the training of service dogs or support dogs for
17 use by veterans; or
18 2. uses trained therapy horses for interaction with veterans;
19 and
20 (iii) has been selected by the Department to provide services under
21 this section.
22 [(5)] (6) “Program” means the Maryland Veterans Service Animal
23 Program established under subsection (b) of this section.
24 [(6)] (7) “Program participant” means an eligible veteran OR ELIGIBLE
25 FAMILY MEMBER who participates in the Program.
26 [(7)] (8) “Service dog” means a dog that is individually trained to do work
27 or perform tasks for the benefit of an individual with a disability, including physical,
28 sensory, psychiatric, intellectual, or other mental disability.

SENATE BILL 182 3
1 [(8)] (9) “Successful Program participant” means a Program participant
2 who successfully completes the training or therapy protocol specified by a nonprofit training
3 entity.
4 [(9)] (10) “Support dog” means a dog that is individually trained and that
5 serves as an emotional support or therapy animal that a medical professional, within the
6 medical professional’s scope of practice, has determined provides benefit for an individual
7 with a sensory, psychiatric, intellectual, or other mental disability.
8 [(10)] (11) “Therapy horse” includes a horse determined appropriate for
9 interactions with veterans by a stable licensed by the State that:
10 (i) is a Professional Association of Therapeutic Horsemanship,
11 International (PATH, Intl.) member center; or
12 (ii) has Equine Assisted Growth and Learning Association
13 (EAGALA) certified professionals who provide services to veterans.
14 (b) There is a Maryland Veterans Service Animal Program in the Department.
15 (c) The purposes of the Program are to:
16 (1) refer eligible veterans AND ELIGIBLE FAMILY MEMBERS who inquire
17 about participation in the Program to one or more nonprofit training entities;
18 (2) provide additional funding mechanisms to assist veterans AND
19 ELIGIBLE FAMILY MEMBERS participating in the Program;
20 (3) encourage successful Program participants to assist in outreach and
21 referral of other eligible veterans AND ELIGIBLE FAMILY MEMBERS who could benefit
22 from participation in the Program;
23 (4) assist in the reduction of the Maryland veteran suicide rate; and
24 (5) identify potential capital projects and services to facilitate more
25 services for veterans AND ELIGIBLE FAMILY MEMBERS in the State.
26 (d) (1) The Department shall select at least one nonprofit training entity to:
27 (i) implement a training or therapy protocol for the purposes of the
28 Program that will teach each Program participant methodologies, strategies, and
29 techniques for:
30 1. partnering with service dogs or support dogs; or
31 2. interacting with therapy horses;

4 SENATE BILL 182
1 (ii) select qualified Program participants from those eligible
2 veterans AND ELIGIBLE FAMILY MEMBERS referred to the nonprofit entity under the
3 Program;
4 (iii) select an appropriate service dog, support dog, or therapy horse,
5 as applicable, for each Program participant;
6 (iv) facilitate each Program participant’s training or therapy using
7 the nonprofit training entity’s training or therapy protocol; and
8 (v) unless the nonprofit training entity uses trained therapy horses,
9 partner each successful Program participant with the service dog or support dog on the
10 Program participant’s successful completion of the nonprofit training entity’s training
11 protocol.
12 (2) To be eligible for selection under paragraph (1) of this subsection, a
13 nonprofit entity must:
14 (i) be based in the State;
15 (ii) serve the needs of the veteran population in the State; and
16 (iii) generate its own revenue and reinvest the proceeds of that
17 revenue in the growth and development of its programs.
18 (e) (1) A nonprofit training entity may disqualify a Program participant from
19 participation in the Program if the nonprofit training entity determines that the Program
20 participant’s involvement in the Program:
21 (i) presents a danger to the Program participant’s mental or
22 physical well–being;
23 (ii) has caused or may potentially cause harm to others, an animal,
24 or property;
25 (iii) presents a danger to the service dog’s, support dog’s, or therapy
26 horse’s mental or physical well–being; or
27 (iv) does not meet the training requirement of the nonprofit.
28 (2) A Program participant may discontinue involvement in the Program for
29 any reason.
30 (f) (1) There is a Maryland Veterans Service Animal Program Fund.

